Testimony To The Senate Veterans, HUD Appropriations Subcomittee<br>
Regarding The NASA Budget<br>
For FY 2002<br>
Dr. Robert Zubrin, President; The Mars Society<br>
...<br>
 Our space program has been literally and figuratively going around in circles since the end of the Apollo Program.<br>
 Few people under the age of 40 have any direct recollection of our Nation’s greatest technological and exploration achievement; landing humans on the Moon.<br>
 In addition, more people are even beginning to deny that the Moon landing ever took place. While this opinion used to be limited to fringe elements of our society, it has now become main stream. Earlier this year, the Fox Network aired a program that claimed that the Moon landing was a hoax. An estimated 20 million people watched this program. It was so popular that the network aired it for a second time, several weeks later.<br>
 Since then, teachers around the country have been forced to do damage control, responding to many of their students who now believe that the Moon landing was a hoax.<br>
<br>
Should we be surprised by this phenomenon? Absolutely not! In the late 1960s and early 1970s, the possibilities in space exploration looked limitless.<br>
What should have been one giant leap for mankind, the Moon landings have turned out to be just a few small steps.<br>
 After launching the Nation, and the world, into what looked like our greatest age of exploration and learning, we retreated and have never returned.<br>
We now need to engage in a new and great age of exploration and discovery -- an age that will again inspire our Nation and the world.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Zubrin wrote in &quot;Entering Space&quot; that millennial hysteria in Europe peaked at the end of the first millennium of the Christian era. Apocalyptic sects grew up all over Europe, and it seemed that this fever of the &quot;end-times&quot; infected everything.<br>
 There were no buildings taller than 2 stories built for a long period before the turn of that millennium.<br>
 After the millennium turned over, it's almost as if people breathed a sigh of relief. Maybe things hadn't really changed any, but we were still alive.<br>
 Attention to the arts picked up, and immense soaring cathedrals sprang upall across Europe.<br>
 We've passed another millennial fever era, faced down the apocalypse again.<br>
Maybe it's time to build some more cathedrals to inspire people.<br>
<br>
(I remember a &quot;Dilbert&quot; cartoon about this. Dogbert was trying to get gullible people to give him all their wealth &quot;I've picked the year 2000 because it's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>big</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>round</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and that seems to get people scared more easily.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Atomic Conspiracy  (10/17/02)<br>
 It happens that I have paid a lot of attention to this particular subject over the years. I am convinced that public respect for science and progress actually peaked in the 1930s and has been declining ever since. One of my current projects is a book about this, tentatively entitled High Noon: Science and Public Perception in the 1930s.<br>
Consider: In 1934, when the Corning Glass Works poured the 200 inch mirror for the future Hale telescope, there was enough public interest for Lowell Thomas to broadcast the proceedings live for 16 hours over a national radio network. Later, when the mirror was shipped to California on a special train, radio bulletins tracked its progress and people lined the tracks and cheered as it went by. <br>
In a speech to a crowd of unemployed workers, a California politician denounced the telescope for &quot;wasting millions when people were starving.&quot; He was pelted with rocks and garbage and had to be hustled away by the police.<br>
This was at at a time when people really were starving in this country.<br>
They saw science and progress as a solution to their problems, and not as a competitor for hand-outs.<br>
They were right, too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sounds like a good project. Whether your thesis is true <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;public respect for science and progress actually peaked in the 1930s and has been declining ever since&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, it's important that stuff like this gets out there.<br>
I've heard that things peaked in the '60s, like you also wrote:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; The conventional view is that World War 2 era<br>
scientific developments like the atomic bomb made<br>
people a great deal more skeptical of science.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->)<br>
<br>
During the '50s-'60s, was when ICBMs became operational, only increasing the percieved dangers of the technologies we were making.<br>
<br>
 Also, the fact that while we were doing Apollo, we were simultaneously fighting in Vietnam, affected people's perceptions of the value of it.<br>
 Zubrin also wrote in &quot;Entering Space&quot; that even before we made it to the Moon, the government was actively trying to gut the space program.<br>
The White House sent a memo to State, pushing forward the Outer Space Treaty, specifically with the 'common heritage' clause and the bit about no property claims in space. They wanted to generate a loss of interest in space, &quot;to save money for other things in the budget&quot;, including &quot;to mitigate the political strain of the war in Vietnam&quot;.<br>
<br>
I know it sounds too much like a conspiracy theory, but the fact remains, we didn't just lose interest in space, it was actively killed by the same government.<br>
We also have a recording of Kennedy saying that he didn't care about space, he just wanted to beat the Reds.<br>
<br>
Look at the decisions made about rocketry in the same era; everything says that they just wanted a one-off, throw-away system, and no consideration to going on to bigger &amp; better things (Orion, Sea Dragon, &amp; later Space colonies &amp; SPS as well as the many good ideas for Space Shuttle concepts. Everything turned down in favor of the most expensive, least capable system.)<br>
