A great deal was learned in the process, of course, and there were plans to follow up with more practical developments. There was, for example, the follow-on <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/craft/marsusa.htm">Mars Project</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, which postulated a landing in 1982. This involved a direct extrapolation of the Apollo hardware, including nuclear upper stages and<br>
a re-usable Saturn V first stage. <br>
Richard Nixon cancelled this in favor of the Shuttle, a system that was sold to Congress as a great leap forward in cost reduction; claims which now seem foolish, if not criminal.<br>
The space program went wrong at a very early date, probably in the 1950s. Recently, I have noticed a kind of &quot;back to the future&quot; mentality among space enthusiasts, a desire to start over at the beginning; with the benefit, of course, of current technology. <br>
<br>
This may be why we see so much interest in things like the Collier's magazine series (including the new movie <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.users.bigpond.net.au/surfacesrendered/MCSHomepage.html&quot;"> Man Conquers Space</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->) and the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.canadianarrow.com">Canadian Arrow</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> project to revive the V-2 for an attempt at the X-prize. <br>
